13 ξ 6. praeda] The Roman general had absolute power to dispose of booty taken in war, provided that he devoted it to a purpose other than personal. Thus he could, as here, distribute it among the soldiers, or he could pay it into the aerarium, or else devote it to the service of some god. Note the distinction between praeda, the actual booty taken, and vezozabiae, the money realized by the sale of booty. Cf. Gell. 13. 24· ‘z 5: praeda dicitur corpora ipsa rerum, quae capta sunt: manubiae vero appellatae sunt pecunia a quaestore ex venditione praedae redacta.
